tionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Rugg  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rugg","meanings":["South German (<b>Rügg</b>): from the medieval personal name <i>Rüegg</i>, a shortened form of   Rudiger  .","English: from Middle English <i>rugge</i> ‘ridge’, a form found widely in the West Midlands, parts of southwestern England, and as far east as Sussex. It is synonymous with   Ridge   and denotes someone who lived on or by a ridge, or who came from a place so named, such as Rudge (Staffordshire, Somerset), or Rudge in Froxfield (Wiltshire).","English: perhaps occasionally a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>r(o)uge</i> (Old French <i>rouge</i>) ‘red’, presumably for someone with red hair or a ruddy complexion. Compare   Rouse  ."]},{"name":"Ridge","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived on or by a ridge, Middle English <i>rigge</i> (Old English <i>hrycg</i>) ‘ridge’, or a habitational name from any of the minor places so named. It is synonymous with West Midlands   Rudge   and northern   Rigg  . The surname is also fairly common in Ireland, in County Galway, having been taken to Connacht in the early 17th century. The name is sometimes Gaelicized as <b>Mac Iomaire</b>; <i>iomaire</i> being modern Irish for ‘ridge’. Compare   Attridge  .","sometimes perhaps a variant of   Rich   with voicing of the formerly medial consonant."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Rugge was born in 1415, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Rugge, was 30 and his mother, Mrs Robert Rugge, was 28. He had at least 2 sons with Mary Ellen Wright. He died in 1449, in his hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1415–1449":"1415–1449","1419–1445":"1419–1445","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1445–1536":"1445–1536","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1415":"1415","1536":"1536","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","1385":"1385","1419":"1419","1449":"1449","England":"England","Rugge, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1415–1449":"1415–1449","1419–1445":"1419–1445","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1445–1536":"1445–1536","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1387–Female":"1387–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1536":"1536","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","1385":"1385","1419":"1419","1449":"1449","England":"England","Rugge, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1415–1449":"1415–1449","1419–1445":"1419–1445","1435–Male":"1435–Décédé","1445–1536":"1445–1536","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1387–Female":"1387–Décédée","1415":"1415","1536":"1536","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","1385":"1385","1419":"1419","1449":"1449","England":"Angleterre","Rugge, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Rugge est né en 1415, à Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Robert Rugge,